SIMPLE: guardian
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Guardian
<hw>Guard"i*an</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OF.
<ets>guardain</ets>, <ets>gardien</ets>, F. <ets>gardien</ets>, LL.
<ets>guardianus</ets>. See <er>Guard</er>, <pos>v. t.</pos>, and cf.
<er>Wasden</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>One who guards, preserves, or
secures; one to whom any person or thing is committed for protection,
security, or preservation from injury; a warden.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Law)</fld> <def>One who has, or is entitled to, the
custody of the person or property of an infant, a minor without living
parents, or a person incapable of managing his own affairs.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Of the several species of <qex>guardians</qex>, the first are
<qex>guardians</qex> by nature. -- viz., the father and (in some cases)
the mother of the child.</q> <rj><qau>Blackstone.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Guardian ad litem</b></col> <pr>(<?/)</pr>
<fld>(Law)</fld>, <cd>a guardian appointed by a court of justice to
conduct a particular suit.</cd> -- <col><b>Guardians of the
poor</b></col>, <cd>the members of a board appointed or elected to care
for the relief of the poor within a township, or district.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><-- p. 656 --></p>

<p><ent>Guardian</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Guardian
<hw>Guard"i*an</hw> <pr>(g⟦aum⟧rd"⟦icr⟧*⟦ait⟧n <it>or</it>
g⟦aum⟧rd"y⟦ait⟧n; 106)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Performing, or
appropriate to, the office of a protector; <as>as, a <ex>guardian</ex>
care</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Feast of Guardian Angels</b></col> <fld>(R. C. Ch.)</fld>
<cd>a church festival instituted by <person>Pope Paul V.</person>, and
celebrated on October 2d.</cd> -- <col><b>Guardian angel</b></col>.
<sd>(a)</sd> <cd>The particular spiritual being believed in some
branches of the Christian church to have guardianship and protection of
each human being from birth.</cd> <sd>(b)</sd> <cd>Hence, a protector or
defender in general.</cd> <au>O. W. Holmes.</au> -- <col><b>Guardian
spirit</b></col>, <cd>in the belief of many pagan nations, a spirit,
often of a deceased relative or friend, that presides over the interests
of a household, a city, or a region.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Guardianage</ent>⟦br⟧
